00:06:01,362 --> 00:06:03,562
narrator: silk fibres can be creatively crafted    

87
00:06:03,564 --> 00:06:05,898
into a variety of artistic objects,       

88
00:06:05,900 --> 00:06:10,436
from paper to fabric or even items like lamps.    

89
00:06:10,438 --> 00:06:12,103
the fibres are translucent,   

90
00:06:12,105 --> 00:06:14,039
so they can take bright, white light       

91
00:06:14,041 --> 00:06:16,842
and diffuse it into warm, beautiful mood lighting.     

92
00:06:22,316 --> 00:06:24,383
this lamp doesn't have shades.  

93
00:06:24,385 --> 00:06:27,386
instead, it has natural-looking silk flowers   

94
00:06:27,388 --> 00:06:29,321
which conceal its lights.    

95
00:06:29,323 --> 00:06:31,891
the lamp base is made of branches.       

96
00:06:34,061 --> 00:06:36,061
to create this functional artwork,     

97
00:06:36,063 --> 00:06:38,063
the artisan begins with a roving.          

98
00:06:38,065 --> 00:06:39,932
a roving is a bundle of fibres  

99
00:06:39,934 --> 00:06:43,468
harvested from a silk moth caterpillar's cocoon.      

100
00:06:43,470 --> 00:06:46,004
they've been cleaned and straightened.        

101
00:06:46,006 --> 00:06:48,940
she places the roving in a nylon mesh bag,       

102
00:06:48,942 --> 00:06:52,945
then submerges it        
in a specially formulated dye.  

103
00:06:56,750 --> 00:07:00,152
she heats the dye to 185 degrees,         

104
00:07:00,154 --> 00:07:02,221
then sprinkles in more powdered dye        

105
00:07:02,223 --> 00:07:04,924
to produces splashes of bolder colors.        

106
00:07:07,762 --> 00:07:11,130
after a couple of minutes, she removes the roving...    

107
00:07:13,600 --> 00:07:15,935
...and rinses off the excess dye.         

108
00:07:19,707 --> 00:07:23,509
she hangs the roving on a rack until it's completely dry.    

109
00:07:26,514 --> 00:07:30,249
roving is typically spun into thread to make silk fabric,   

110
00:07:30,251 --> 00:07:33,651
but this artisan has a different technique.    

111
00:07:33,653 --> 00:07:38,057
she spreads a sheet of tulle on her work table.        

112
00:07:38,059 --> 00:07:41,926
then she gently separates the fine, hair-like fibres    

113
00:07:41,928 --> 00:07:44,063
and lays them out on the tulle.             

114
00:07:50,137 --> 00:07:54,673
each pile will be turned into a flower for the lamp.      

115
00:07:54,675 --> 00:07:57,209
she folds over the tulle to create a barrier       

116
00:07:57,211 --> 00:08:01,747
that keeps the fibers from sticking to her hands.   

117
00:08:01,749 --> 00:08:03,482
she prepares the fibres     

118
00:08:03,484 --> 00:08:05,951
for the textile medium she'll apply next,        

119
00:08:05,953 --> 00:08:07,820
a polymer adhesive.       

120
00:08:07,822 --> 00:08:09,755
she saturates each pile     

121
00:08:09,757 --> 00:08:13,425
with water containing a few   
drops of dishwashing detergent  

122
00:08:13,427 --> 00:08:15,360
to open up the fibres.      

123
00:08:15,362 --> 00:08:18,030
then she sponges up the excess water         

124
00:08:18,032 --> 00:08:21,233
and soaks up any other remaining moisture with a towel              

125
00:08:21,235 --> 00:08:24,436
so the medium does not become diluted.     

126
00:08:24,438 --> 00:08:28,707
now she's ready         
to apply the polymer adhesive.  

127
00:08:28,709 --> 00:08:32,110
as the fibres absorb the medium, they fuse together,       

128
00:08:32,112 --> 00:08:35,147
forming a sheet of silk fibre paper.       

129
00:08:40,988 --> 00:08:42,921
after folding back the tulle,  

130
00:08:42,923 --> 00:08:46,091
she begins molding each paper into a flower.          

131
00:08:50,865 --> 00:08:53,065
she spreads the paper over a balloon          

132
00:08:53,067 --> 00:08:55,267
and lets it dry overnight.    

133
00:08:59,740 --> 00:09:01,673
with a few simple steps,     

134
00:09:01,675 --> 00:09:04,275
she has transformed a colorless roving        

135
00:09:04,277 --> 00:09:08,613
into colorful sheets of moldable silk fibre paper.  

136
00:09:08,615 --> 00:09:10,916
the next day, she pops the balloon.      

137
00:09:13,086 --> 00:09:16,055
the silk fibre paper holds its round shape.      

138
00:09:24,831 --> 00:09:26,831
using the textile medium again,             

139
00:09:26,833 --> 00:09:31,036
she glues her silk fibre flowers to juniper branches.       

140
00:09:36,576 --> 00:09:39,311
she secures them with a needle and thread,    

141
00:09:39,313 --> 00:09:41,446
matching the thread color to the silk           

142
00:09:41,448 --> 00:09:42,881
so that it blends in.      

143
00:09:46,854 --> 00:09:48,453
she further sculpts the flowers             

144
00:09:48,455 --> 00:09:51,924
with a stitch or two in select spots.         

145
00:09:51,926 --> 00:09:56,528
and dabs textile medium on the thread to secure it.   

146
00:09:56,530 --> 00:09:59,464
then she glues in a second, slightly smaller flower,     

147
00:09:59,466 --> 00:10:01,667
creating two layers of petals.  

148
00:10:04,738 --> 00:10:07,138
she takes some fibres she dyed green          

149
00:10:07,140 --> 00:10:10,542
and glues them under the blooms to form wispy leaves.      

150
00:10:17,685 --> 00:10:21,019
finally, to turn this sculpture into a functioning lamp,     

151
00:10:21,021 --> 00:10:23,956
she places a battery powered l.e.d. push light        

152
00:10:23,958 --> 00:10:26,125
in the center of each flower.  

153
00:10:40,841 --> 00:10:42,841
the lamp needs no inner wiring  

154
00:10:42,843 --> 00:10:46,378
and doesn't need to be plugged into an outlet.  

155
00:10:46,380 --> 00:10:48,513
you simply press the middle of each flower    

156
00:10:48,515 --> 00:10:51,650
to turn its hidden push light on or off.            

157
00:10:51,652 --> 00:10:55,687
a simple sculpture by day, and a gentle light by night.   

158
00:11:12,540 --> 00:11:17,676
narrator: round hay balers automatically 

159
00:11:17,678 --> 00:11:22,080
they can also wrap the rolled hay in twine or plastic.     

160
00:11:22,082 --> 00:11:24,349
this american invention allows farmers          

161
00:11:24,351 --> 00:11:28,554
to put down their pitchforks and leave the work to the machines.            

162
00:11:34,427 --> 00:11:38,162
the invention of the round baler was a farming breakthrough.   

163
00:11:38,164 --> 00:11:41,533
round bales of hay       
stayed drier than square ones.  

164
00:11:45,372 --> 00:11:46,771
making a round hay baler     

165
00:11:46,773 --> 00:11:50,108
starts with a computerized fiber-optic laser.        

166
00:11:50,110 --> 00:11:53,845
it cuts steel sheaths into the shape of the side panels   

167
00:11:53,847 --> 00:11:58,049
and makes holes for hardware and machine components.     

168
00:11:58,051 --> 00:11:59,918
once the cuts have been made,  

169
00:11:59,920 --> 00:12:02,721
workers remove the leftover materials.     

170
00:12:02,723 --> 00:12:05,657
they'll be recycled into new steel sheets.      

171
00:12:05,659 --> 00:12:07,526
next, the baler side panel    

172
00:12:07,528 --> 00:12:10,395
goes to a computerized hydraulic folder.        

173
00:12:12,399 --> 00:12:16,068
it bends the edges of the panel to prepare it for assembly.   

174
00:12:18,805 --> 00:12:21,406
with the side panel clamped in a fixture,      

175
00:12:21,408 --> 00:12:26,411
a worker slides bolts into a part called the doubler plate.             

176
00:12:26,413 --> 00:12:30,616
this plate will be used to reinforce the panel.     

177
00:12:30,618 --> 00:12:34,619
he welds the heads of the bolts to the doubler plate.      

178
00:12:34,621 --> 00:12:36,021
the bolts protrude up      

179
00:12:36,023 --> 00:12:38,924
so bearings and other parts can be attached later.      

180
00:12:43,897 --> 00:12:46,098
he adds other reinforcing parts,             

181
00:12:46,100 --> 00:12:49,601
supports for rollers, and a box for twine.       

182
00:12:51,505 --> 00:12:53,772
then it's over to the paint department.     

183
00:12:53,774 --> 00:12:56,375
they prime and paint both sides of the panel     

184
00:12:56,377 --> 00:12:57,976
with an epoxy finish       

185
00:12:57,978 --> 00:13:00,612
in order to protect the steel from corrosion.         

186
00:13:03,450 --> 00:13:06,385
after the paint dries, cranes lift two panels      

187
00:13:06,387 --> 00:13:11,256
over to a fixture that holds several baler rollers.      

188
00:13:11,258 --> 00:13:13,324
workers insert the ends of the rollers     

189
00:13:13,326 --> 00:13:16,328
into holes in the side panels.  

190
00:13:16,330 --> 00:13:18,263
they add an auger for moving the hay        

191
00:13:18,265 --> 00:13:21,332
away from the sides of the baler.          

192
00:13:21,334 --> 00:13:25,336
they secure all of these components with bolts.      

193
00:13:25,338 --> 00:13:28,272
next, they install a belt-tightening assembly.   

194
00:13:28,274 --> 00:13:30,275
the bars will hold the hay-shaping belts      

195
00:13:30,277 --> 00:13:31,643
at the correct tension.     

196
00:13:34,081 --> 00:13:37,082
after adding a bearing to the bottom feed roller,    

197
00:13:37,084 --> 00:13:39,151
a worker installs sprockets.   

198
00:13:39,153 --> 00:13:42,554
he also loops chains around them.           

199
00:13:42,556 --> 00:13:44,289
the sprockets and chains     

200
00:13:44,291 --> 00:13:48,360
will drive the 14 rollers in the baler.          

201
00:13:48,362 --> 00:13:51,163
the next part is known as the hay pickup,   

202
00:13:51,165 --> 00:13:52,497
because its steel teeth     

203
00:13:52,499 --> 00:13:56,501
lift hay from the field and into the baler.       

204
00:13:56,503 --> 00:13:59,838
it fits on the front of the machine.         

205
00:13:59,840 --> 00:14:02,306
now a worker installs the wheels.       

206
00:14:02,308 --> 00:14:04,643
he brushes a lubricant onto spindles          

207
00:14:04,645 --> 00:14:07,712
and inserts them in the wheel axles.       

208
00:14:07,714 --> 00:14:11,983
bolts secure the spindles to the axles.          

209
00:14:11,985 --> 00:14:14,452
then he mounts the wheels to the spindles         

210
00:14:14,454 --> 00:14:16,822
and locks them in place with nuts.            

211
00:14:21,394 --> 00:14:23,462
once the two wheels are installed,          

212
00:14:23,464 --> 00:14:26,531
a crane lifts the machine into an upright position     

213
00:14:26,533 --> 00:14:29,368
in order to install the rear chamber.        

214
00:14:34,608 --> 00:14:39,010
a crane lowers the rear chamber onto the baler assembly.     

215
00:14:39,012 --> 00:14:42,213
as the hay is shaped with a round bale by the machine,   

216
00:14:42,215 --> 00:14:46,218
it will gradually expand in this chamber.         

217
00:14:46,220 --> 00:14:50,055
these rubber belts will roll the hay into round bales.    

218
00:14:52,892 --> 00:14:55,627
the team loops them around tensioning rollers,    

219
00:14:55,629 --> 00:14:57,763
arranging them closely together.            

220
00:15:03,437 --> 00:15:05,904
a worker joins the ends of each belt      

221
00:15:05,906 --> 00:15:08,874
by pushing steel pins through riveted lacing.     

222
00:15:15,315 --> 00:15:19,351
an employee applies vinyl decals to the outside of the baler.   

223
00:15:24,391 --> 00:15:26,858
the decals display the company name         

224
00:15:26,860 --> 00:15:29,528
and the machine model in bold graphics.        

225
00:15:32,466 --> 00:15:35,266
the machine is equipped with hydraulic cylinders     

226
00:15:35,268 --> 00:15:39,538
so the rear chamber can be raised and lowered.    

227
00:15:39,540 --> 00:15:42,174
a technician syncs the tractor cab monitor  

228
00:15:42,176 --> 00:15:46,611
to sensors added to the baler during the assembly.       

229
00:15:46,613 --> 00:15:50,148
the sensors indicate      
the position of the back gate,  

230
00:15:50,150 --> 00:15:52,416
the status of the bale wrapping equipment,           

231
00:15:52,418 --> 00:15:54,486
and the moisture level in the hay.           

232
00:15:56,423 --> 00:15:58,890
after a complete operational check,              

233
00:15:58,892 --> 00:16:02,627
this baler is ready to give farmers or ranchers a break   

234
00:16:02,629 --> 00:16:06,131
by automatically creating round bales of hay.       

235
00:16:22,449 --> 00:16:23,982
narrator: with footwear,     

